      sudo pacman -Rns btrfs-progs xfsprogs f2fs-tools jfsutils udftools gpart os-prober mtools

  Reversible — reinstall any time with:  sudo pacman -S <pkg>

------------------------------------------------------------
 KEEP — DO NOT REMOVE (your setup depends on these)
------------------------------------------------------------
  e2fsprogs      root filesystem is ext4 — fsck/mkfs.ext4. Removing = unbootable risk.
  dosfstools     ESP is vfat and /etc/fstab fsck's it at boot (pass 2). Required.
  refind         your bootloader.
  efibootmgr     manages UEFI boot entries.
  gparted, gnome-disk-utility, gptfdisk, parted   general disk utilities — useful, keep.

------------------------------------------------------------
 TIER B — DO NOT REMOVE INDIVIDUALLY (shared with the recovery stack)
------------------------------------------------------------
  These look like FS cruft but are pulled in by disk-imaging tools; removing them
  alone would force-remove those tools too:
    nilfs-utils    Required By: partclone        (also: nilfs FS, unused)
    ntfs-3g        Required By: clonezilla, mintstick, partclone
                   ALSO useful to mount NTFS USB / Windows drives — keep if you do that.
    exfatprogs     Required By: mintstick
                   ALSO needed for exFAT USB sticks / SD cards — keep if you use those.

------------------------------------------------------------
 TIER C — OPTIONAL: the whole disk-recovery / imaging stack
------------------------------------------------------------
  ArcoLinux bundles a rescue toolset. It is NOT needed for normal desktop/learning
  use, but it IS handy for cloning/recovery. Your call. Installed:
    clonezilla  partclone  partimage  testdisk  mintstick   (ddrescue — keep, tiny & useful)

  If you don't use these, remove the stack — pacman -Rns will also clean up the
  now-orphaned Tier B tools automatically:
      sudo pacman -Rns clonezilla partclone partimage testdisk mintstick
  After that, nilfs-utils (and possibly ntfs-3g/exfatprogs, unless you want them for
  external drives) become orphans and can be dropped with:  sudo pacman -Rns $(pacman -Qdtq)

